## Pweb architecture
A Pweb is an HTML5 web page which is able to display personalized data in a rich form and allows the user to interact with it.

> Note

For more information, see: [Pweb Solution Overview](/doxee-platform/docs/pweb-solution-overview).

A Pweb leverages HTML, JavaScript, CSS, images and Json data.&nbsp;&nbsp;

In a basic form, a Pweb structure could be exemplified in the diagram below.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### HEAD section
Inside of the HTML page, the head tag contains CSS and JavaScript, which will be further referred to as dependencies,&nbsp;and a JSON object which contains the personalized data.

An example of personalized data is shown below:

**Personalized Data**

`{
    "FILE": {
        "DOCUMENT": [{
            "TEMPLATE": [{
                "CUSTOMER_DATA": [{
                    "FIRST_NAME": "Nathan",
                    "LAST_NAME": "Drake",
                    "EMAIL": "ndrake@privateer.com",
                    "HOME_ADDRESS": "160 Guard Ave, Apt. 3, Key West, Florida"
                }]
            }]
        }]
    }
}`### BODY section
The body part of the HMTL page contains the data representation of the Json data.

In other words, HTML containers are bound to the value of the data and, therefore, the user will be able to read it as standard text, like the example below:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Dependencies
A web page like the example above, uses several images and dependencies to run interactively.

There are two ways to insert dependencies into a Pweb:

- Embedded dependencies

- Linked dependencies

#### Embedded dependencies
In this case the Pweb is a self-consistent HTML page which can be run by the browser even without internet connection.

The page can be sent via email as an attachment.

The structure of the page will look like the image below:

`&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
 &lt;title&gt;My Pweb&lt;/title&gt;
 &lt;style type="text/css"&gt;
  .MyClass {..}
  .MyId {..}
 &lt;/style&gt;
 &lt;script type="text/javascript"&gt;
  ( function ( e ) {...} ); // embedded dependency 1
  ( function ( e ) {...} ); // embedded dependency 2
  ( function ( e ) {...} ); // embedded dependency N
 &lt;/script&gt;
 &lt;script type="doc-data" id="doc-data"&gt;
  {
      "FILE": {
          "DOCUMENT": [{
              "TEMPLATE": [{
                  "CUSTOMER_DATA": [{
                      "FIRST_NAME": "Nathan",
                      "LAST_NAME": "Drake",
                      "EMAIL": "ndrake@privateer.com",
                      "HOME_ADDRESS": "160 Guard Ave, Apt. 3, Key West, Florida"
                  }]
              }]
          }]
      }
  }
 &lt;/script&gt; 
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;valueOf.FIRST_NAME&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;!-- Represents "FIRST_NAME" from doc-data --&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;valueOf.LAST_NAME&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;!-- Represents "LAST_NAME" from doc-data --&gt;
 &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,AGSIGHAGKSDGNKNDSGOJDFASADJ..."&gt; &lt;!-- Image embedded in Base64 --&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;`CSS and JavaScript dependencies are hardcoded in the page in the top section, all the images are inserted in Base64 format.

The benefits of this approach are mentioned above: no internet connection needed by the user and the possibility to send the entire file via email.&nbsp;

The flaws of this approach are the large size of the page, because it's embedding all the dependencies and the images. Therefore, if you want to make it downloadable or show it through a web URL, the time before the user can experience the page may be high.

Also, all of the Pweb documents will be produced containing all the dependencies, no matter if the only difference between them is made up by the values of the data schema in the doc-data section. This will lead to a waste of storage since every Pweb will differ from the other ones for a very small fraction only while all of the dependencies will be duplicated.

#### Linked dependencies
This approach leverages external and relative dependencies and CSS files as well as external images. An example below.

`&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
 &lt;title&gt;My Pweb&lt;/title&gt;
 &lt;link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="theme.css"&gt; // external CSS
 &lt;script type="text/javascript" src="./scripts/my.dependecy01.js" /&gt; // external JavaScript
 &lt;script type="text/javascript" src="./scripts/my.dependecy02.js" /&gt; // external JavaScript
 &lt;script type="text/javascript" src="./scripts/my.dependecy0N.js" /&gt; // external JavaScript
 &lt;script src="https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/angularjs/1.5.7/angular.min.js" /&gt; // cdn JavaScript
 &lt;script src="https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/3.2.1/jquery.min.js" /&gt; // cdn JavaScript
 &lt;script type="doc-data" id="doc-data"&gt;
  {
      "FILE": {
          "DOCUMENT": [{
              "TEMPLATE": [{
                  "CUSTOMER_DATA": [{
                      "FIRST_NAME": "Nathan",
                      "LAST_NAME": "Drake",
                      "EMAIL": "ndrake@privateer.com",
                      "HOME_ADDRESS": "160 Guard Ave, Apt. 3, Key West, Florida"
                  }]
              }]
          }]
      }
  }
 &lt;/script&gt; 
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;valueOf.FIRST_NAME&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;!-- Represents "FIRST_NAME" from doc-data --&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;valueOf.LAST_NAME&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;!-- Represents "LAST_NAME" from doc-data --&gt;
 &lt;img src="./images/myImage.jpg"&gt; &lt;!-- external image --&gt;    
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;`Using this approach it is possible to inject the JavaScript dependencies remotely, and specifically using both CDN and relative paths to the local files.

Using relative path is very important because of the structure of the Doxee delivery system.

The CSS stylesheets and the images can be inserted in the same way, via relative paths.

This kind of Pweb document cannot be sent via email or viewed offline, but it's fast to serve via [Personalized URL Delivery](https://code.doxee.com/confluence/display/DD/Personalized+URL+Delivery), whose url may be sent via email or SMS.

Still it's lightweight in terms of storage because the dependencies are shared among all of the Pweb produced.

## Pweb distribution
### Pweb with embedded dependencies
After the Doxee Platform runs its job, the embedded Pweb can be delivered as an email attachment, downloaded via pURL or viewed on a web page:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Pweb with linked dependencies
The linked Pweb can be delivered via email, SMS and web as a pURL:

![](data:image/png;base64,)
